07048nam a22010455i 9789048539291DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485392917 a10.1515/97890485392912doi  a(DE-B1597)542048  a(OCoLC)1136962159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBP173.7 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a320.55722300aPathways to Contemporary Islam :bNew Trends in Critical Engagement /ced. by Mohamed Nawab Mohamed Osman. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Society in Asia ;v600tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Constructing Pathways to Contemporary Islam -- tSection 1. Historical Trends in Contemporary Perspective -- t1. Pathways to Modern Islam -- t2. A Theoretical Pathway to Contemporary Islam -- tSection 2. Contesting the Islamic Intellectual Tradition -- t3. A New Approach to Islamic Intellectual Tradition -- t4. The Best and Most Trying of Times -- t5. The Function of Myths in the Justification of Muslim Extremism -- tSection 3. Beyond the Arab Revolutions: Political Islam Revised -- t6. Building Trust in the Democratic Process -- t7. The Failure of Political Islam Revisited -- t8. Regaining the Islamic Centre? -- tSection 4. Contemporary Spaces of Critical Engagement -- t9. Enhancing Dialogue Between Religious Traditions -- t10. The Ethical in Shari’a Practices -- t11. The New Horizons of Piety -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPathways to Contemporary Islam highlights that the current tensions in Islam and the Muslim world are the result of historical dynamics as opposed to an alleged incompatibility between religious tradition and modernity. The emphasis on pathways indicates that critical engagement and contestation have always been intrinsic to the history of Islam. The aim of the book is to elaborate the contemporary pathways and analyse the trends that contest the Islamic intellectual tradition, the relationship between religion and politics, and the individual and collective practice of religion. The collection of essays analyses the current efforts of critical re-engagement with the Islamic intellectual tradition and underlines the historical diversity of Islamic orthodoxies that led to the establishment of various pathways in the practice and role of religion in Muslim societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIslam and politics. 0aIslamxHistory. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aCritical engagement, Islam and politics, piety and moral agency, Islamic intellectual tradition.1 aAbdul Hamid, Ahmad Fauzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlatas, Syed Farid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllawi, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmer, Sahar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakar, Osman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHefner, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLumina, Iulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoosa, Ebrahim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNawab, Mohamad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsman, Mohamed Nawab Mohamed, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoy, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul